Flames shot from Thassalin's throat as the huge Thraki set a specific forest area in motion and then circled above it to detect movements. Strangely, the eerie screeching behind him ceased as he slowed down. Thassalin had forgotten about the passengers on his back.
"What's this, Tenuk, you've already turned yourself into a Thraki before!"
"when I fly myself, it's completely different from suddenly being lifted up by a huge pink dragon!"
"So bad was it really, Kayel?"
Kayel was obviously not of Nyssis opinion. He looked less black than usual, and his claws had dug so deeply into Thassalins back that the Thraki was bleeding. However, it seemed to make no difference to Thassalin. Nevertheless, he had realized that he had frightened his new friends, and landed on an open clearing.
"I'm sorry, but I smelled something. I had to take care of that!"
"But did you have to drag us along too?" Tenuk growled as he climbed down from Thassalin's back and slid down onto his tail. "And we left Retvik behind! Our strong, mighty warrior was left behind! How is he ever going to catch up with us again?"
" He'll think of something...," grumbled Nyssi. "Retvik isn't the fastest, but he's not stupid."
"Already, but can Retvik drive?"
Nyssi winkled her eyes and turned back to Tenuk. "Of course he can drive."
"Have you ever seen Retvik drive a vehicle? He doesn't have a truck like you, and I haven't seen him drive a nice little car like Kayel's either. Besides, he only started using the car for work because you always drive us. He only has his bicycle."
Loud laughter interrupted her. Thassalin suddenly seemed to find something wildly funny, but no one knew what he was laughing about. It took a little too long for Thassalin to calm down.
"I'm sorry, but I've imagined your huge friend in armor on such a tiny little bicycle for Tethan children. That was just plain ridiculous! I wish I had some sort of telepathy. A magnificent image! One that I can't share!"
Kayel chuckled, knowing exactly what was going through Thassalin's mind. "Yes, that's true. But what did you smell, and why did you suddenly take off so abruptly?"
Thassalin grunted, lifted off, and disappeared. When he returned after a short time, he threw something lifeless at Nyssi's feet. It was an Orothrack, a very rare, golden-white dragon-like creature. But it was missing its head. "ANOTHER DEAD ONE. I HEAR THEIR CRIES. I SMELL THEIR BLOOD. SOMETHING URGES ME TO PROTECT AND TO HUNT. AS YISINI COMMANDS. THEY ARE VERY NEAR."
The mighty Thraki froze suddenly. Nyssi and Kayel also froze, watching intently at a gap in the clearing. Something large and black stared at them and growled. Whatever it was, it spread two massive wings and shot toward Thassalin, ignoring the three smaller creatures between them. Kayel and Tenuk managed to take cover just in time, but Nyssi was dragged along and nearly thrown onto Thassalin.
Thassalin reacted to this attack by grabbing Nyssi and hurling him with his incredibly long and dexterous tail onto his back, before leaping into the air himself. The black, two-winged creature pursued them at high speed.
Kayel clicked his tongue in annoyance as he took his rifle from his back and opened a pouch containing a belt of ammunition. He slung the belt over his chest, but quickly noticed that Nyssi, the Thraki, and the monster were out of sight.
"Hey, Tenuk, could you turn into something that can fly?" asked Kayel.
"Would you like to follow her?"
"Yes, of course!"
"But... One of them is a huge monster!"
"Yes, and? I'm standing here with a top-notch rifle in my hand and could shoot right away. But, well, how should I put it – I would have to see it first in order to hit it."
Tenuk hesitated, then stepped back to gain more space. With a soft, painful grunt, his body stretched out, his fur turned into scales and his arms into wings. He quickly transformed into a normal, bright blue thraki, but his eyes remained red.
"Get on."
Like a regular-looking Thraki, Tenuk now had a proper scaly shield running along his back. Practically speaking, he also had a pair of spines growing on his back, which Kayel could use to hold on to. It took Tenuk a little too long to get the flight started, but once in the air, he quickly oriented himself and tried to take up the pursuit.
Tenuk and Kayel quickly realized they weren't alone. A second dark creature shot up between them, and Tenuk barely avoided a collision.
"That must be the other terrifying giant monster that Lanex was afraid of?" Kayel frowned. He tried to shoot at the second beast, missed, and quickly reloaded.
Tenuk did not answer. He was too preoccupied with focusing on the flight toward Nyssi and Thassalin, even though the other creature was pursuing them. Kayel turned awkwardly to keep the monster in sight. For Kayel, the fact that it was following them was an advantage, as it made it easier for him to aim and shoot. Two shots went through the upper wings of the creature. It roared in pain and sank back beneath the trees. Kayel wasn't sure if it was still following them, but it would certainly not be able to keep up with them.
A good distance ahead of them, Nyssi desperately clung on, while Thassalin swung around, spitting fire at the soot-blackened monster. The creature was definitely wounded. It seemed furious, but not ready to give up. The fireballs weren't having the desired effect. As Thassalin stretched out, Nyssi seized the opportunity to draw her own weapon—a good old shotgun. It wasn't necessarily the first choice, but maybe the shot would scare off the black beast.
